But although I have need been scammed yet, I must admit that I might have fallen for this scam. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ufelinityvenomblade.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Felinity Venomblade</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/3/01 8:54:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousecontractsbountiesjobsquestsetc.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2395.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.legendsofmarr.com/membersonly/memberspictures/felinity.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A rather nasty trade scam, be careful</span><hr size=1> Had a similar experience when buying HM backpacks. This person sold me 2 HMs and asked me to &quot;hold&quot; some items for him since he didn't have the space anymore. So he filled the first trade slots with junk and then 2 backpacks. At that time I wasnt aware of any potential problems, I had 2 open inventory slots open for the bags. Of course my slots got filled with junk and the bags dropped. I didn't realize this until he told me &quot;Hey, you dropped one, here it is&quot; and actually handed over one bag ... I never saw the second one. Only after a few minutes I realized what happened. I started talking to him and he denied my accusations that he scammed me. <br>
<br>
Of course if he had just left the junk in the bags, and asked for them after the trade, this wouldn't have happened. So either we both made the same mistake or it was a nasty scam.<br>
<br>
So I petitioned and a guide asked me to tell the story. He couldn't help, he told me they can't trace items once dropped. And there was no proof that this was done deliberately or by accident.<br>
